Church is the heart. You take the heart out of the body, the body dies.â€â€œWhen we took prayers out of schools, guns came into schools,â€ the mayor continued. Explaining that he implemented policies with a â€œgodlike approach,â€ he promised that homelessness and domestic violence would be gone from the city â€œif we were bringing our best fight in the ring.â€ Adams insisted he â€œstrongly believe[d] in all [his] heartâ€ that â€œGod said, â€˜Iâ€m going to take the most broken person and Iâ€™m going to elevate him to the place of being the mayor of the most powerful city on the globeâ€™,â€ joking that â€œHe could have made me mayor of Topeka, Kansas.â€Adamsâ€™ comments did not appear to be improvised, with his aide Ingrid Lewis-Martin introducing him to the assembled religious leaders in a similar vein. â€œDefinitely one of the chosen,â€ Adams was a mayor whose government â€œdoesnâ€™t believeâ€ in separating church and state, she said.Many of the guests were reportedly appalled. Rabbi Abby Stein told the New York Times on Tuesday that she and â€œseveral people sharing her tableâ€ had reacted withimmediate horror, repeating â€œno, no, no, noâ€ as the mayorâ€™s â€œunhinged and dangerousâ€ remarks washed over them.New York Civil Liberties Union director Donna Lieberman said she was â€œspeechlessâ€ to hear Adams inveighing against one of the nationâ€™s foundational concepts. â€œAs mayor, heâ€™s bound to uphold the Constitution, which provides for separation of church and state,â€ she pointed out.But Adamsâ€™ spokesman Fabien Levy insisted the mayorâ€™s remarks had been misinterpreted, arguing the former NYPD officer merely meant â€œthe policies we make as an administration are rooted in the mayorâ€™s belief in the creator.â€https://www.rt.com/news/572289-adams-church-state-weird-speech/
